&lt;h2 id=&quot;making-a-post-sticky&quot;&gt;Making a post â€œstickyâ€&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Add &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;sticky: true&lt;/code&gt; to the frontmatter of your blog post.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&quot;exclude-sticky-post-from-paginated-posts&quot;&gt;Exclude sticky post from paginated posts&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By default, sticky posts are still included in the paginated posts. To exclude a sticky post from paginated posts, add &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;hidden: true&lt;/code&gt; to the frontmatter of that blog post.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;example&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/chesterhow/tale/blob/master/_posts/2017-03-29-introducing-tale.md&quot;&gt;â€œIntroducing Taleâ€ post&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Chester</name></author><category term="Tutorial" /><summary type="html">Sticky, or pinned, posts are featured on the top of every page. Tale provides some flexibility when it comes to this feature.</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Managing Excerpt</title><link href="https://shandaming.github.io/2021-04-30/managing-excerpt" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Managing Excerpt" /><published>2021-04-30T00:00:00+08:00</published><updated>2021-04-30T00:00:00+08:00</updated><id>https://shandaming.github.io/2021-04-30/managing-excerpt</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://shandaming.github.io/2021-04-30/managing-excerpt">&lt;p&gt;You can customise the excerpt (the text displayed below each post on the homepage) using the &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;excerpt-separator&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;!--more--&gt; Hereâ€™s how you can do so!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;steps&quot;&gt;Steps&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Add &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;excerpt_separator: &amp;lt;!--more--&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; to the frontmatter of your blog post.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Insert this &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;!--more--&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; at where you would like the excerpt to cut off in your blog post.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&quot;note&quot;&gt;Note&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This follows &lt;a href=&quot;https://jekyllrb.com/docs/posts/#post-excerpts&quot;&gt;Jekyllâ€™s recommended way of managing excerpts&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;example&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/chesterhow/tale/blob/master/_posts/2021-04-30-managing-excerpt.md&quot;&gt;this post&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/chesterhow/tale/blob/master/_posts/2017-03-29-introducing-tale.md&quot;&gt;â€œIntroducing Taleâ€ post&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Chester</name></author><category term="Tutorial" /><summary type="html">You can customise the excerpt (the text displayed below each post on the homepage) using the excerpt-separator.</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Introducing Tale</title><link href="https://shandaming.github.io/2017-03-29/introducing-tale" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Introducing Tale" /><published>2017-03-29T00:00:00+08:00</published><updated>2017-03-29T00:00:00+08:00</updated><id>https://shandaming.github.io/2017-03-29/introducing-tale</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://shandaming.github.io/2017-03-29/introducing-tale">&lt;p&gt;Tale is a minimal &lt;a href=&quot;https://jekyllrb.com/&quot;&gt;Jekyll&lt;/a&gt; theme curated for storytellers. It is designed and developed by &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/chesterhow/&quot;&gt;myself&lt;/a&gt; for a friend who writes short stories.&lt;!--more--&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;tale-features&quot;&gt;Tale features&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Compatible with GitHub Pages&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Responsive design (looks just as good on mobile)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Syntax highlighting, with the help of Pygments&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Markdown and HTML text formatting&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Pagination of posts&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Sticky posts&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Tags&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Excerpt management&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Disqus comments&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Head over to the &lt;a href=&quot;/2017-03-16/example-content&quot;&gt;Example Content&lt;/a&gt; post for a showcase of Taleâ€™s text formatting features.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;browser-support&quot;&gt;Browser Support&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tale works on most if not all modern browsers, including Chrome, Safari and Firefox ğŸ‘ğŸ¼&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&quot;download-or-contribute&quot;&gt;Download or Contribute&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tale is publicly hosted on GitHub, so go ahead and download or fork it at the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/chesterhow/tale&quot;&gt;GitHub repository&lt;/a&gt;. If you spot any bugs or have any suggestions, feel free to create an issue or make a pull request.&lt;/p&gt;

